The sustainable improvement of Beijing's natural ecology attracts more than 500 species of wildlife to "settle" in the city.
2020-07-26 05: 03: 17 Source: Beijing Youth Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
The capital's natural ecology continues to improve to attract wildlife to "settle" in the city
There are more than 500 species of wildlife in Beijing
The reporter of this newspaper (reporter Wang Bin) Beijing Youth Daily learned from the Municipal Bureau of Landscape and Greening that with the continuous improvement of the natural ecological environment in the capital in recent years, the species and number of wildlife have also continued to increase.
At present, the number of terrestrial spinal wildlife living in Beijing has increased to more than 500 species, including state-level protected animals such as brown horse chicken and black stork, as well as state-level protected animals such as gazelle, swan, gray crane and mandarin duck.
Whether the urban forests planted everywhere in the Second Ring, or the small wetlands embedded in the buildings, not only bring natural wild interest to the citizens of the capital, but also attract wildlife to "settle" in the city.
In the middle of summer, the Songshan National Nature Reserve, located in the Yanshan Mountains in the northwest of Yanqing District, is vibrant.
A raccoon was playing leisurely by a mountain stream, while two badgers played with each other.
Looking back, a wild boar couldn't resist the "sting" on his body and was rubbing hard against the bark of the bark.Hu Qiaoli, director of the Songshan National Nature Reserve Administration, said that by the end of 2019, 178 species of wild animals, including gold eagles protected by the national level and chickens and wildebeest protected by the national level, lived in the Green Sea, which covers a total area of more than 6,200 hectares. Nearly a third of the wildlife species in the city could be found here.
"In Songshan, wild animals are the real 'owners', and our staff can only be the 'bodyguards' of people at best."
Hu said that in order to understand the situation of wildlife in the protected area on the ground, more than 30 professional rangers patrol along 16 carefully formulated protection routes every day, and there is a "big circle" once a month, which takes a whole day to travel almost all over the protected area.
"When patrolling, we should not only check and record biodiversity, but also check the installation of artificial bird nests, rescue injured wildlife, install field infrared cameras, and so on."
More than 200 infrared cameras have been installed in Songshan National Nature Reserve to record the living conditions of wildlife in the forest.
Hu Qiaoli said that with the continuous enrichment of biodiversity in the protected areas in recent years, more and more wild animals appear in the camera, leopard cats, raccoons and pig badgers have become "permanent guests", and the "appearance rate" of gazelle, an animal protected by the state at the second level, has become higher and higher.
Zhang Zhiming, Director of the Wildlife and Wetland Protection Division of the Beijing Landscape and Greening Bureau, said that the number of species of terrestrial spinal wildlife in Beijing has increased from 461 in 1994 to more than 500 now. The species and number of wildlife in Beijing have continued to increase in recent years.
The figure of wild animals in cities is becoming more and more common, which is closely related to the upgrading of urban greening in the capital in recent years.
In particular, the new round of million-mu afforestation and greening construction, which began in 2018, proposes to reshape the urban ecological environment, enhance the ecological function of woodland green areas, and highlight the concept of "near-nature".
The plan strives to achieve interconnection and interaction with the surrounding green areas to facilitate wildlife to "visit relatives and friends", and the trees planted are also the favorite source of honey and food plants for animals.
Black land "planted" for agricultural modernization
Xinhua News Agency, Harbin, July 26, telegram question: Black land "planted" out of agricultural modernization
In the middle of summer, two spraying planes passed the 10,000-acre high-yield demonstration field in the second operation station of the fifth management area of Friendship Farm, forming two white lines. The words "the first field in the world" planted with black rice seedlings in the green fields were particularly striking.
Kong Lingqiang, the station director of the operation station, said the aircraft could spray more than 6,000 acres of arable land in a day, with an efficiency of about eight times that of a drone and hundreds of times that of man.
This farm is located in the territory of Friendship County of Heilongjiang Province, China's largest grain-producing province. From the sound of "rice cutting" in the past to the sound of "rumbling" today, Chinese traditional farming and farming have transformed in this black soil belt.
In addition to aircraft, satellites are also used in the modern agricultural production of Friendship Farm.
Kong Lingqiang introduced that, on the one hand, they use satellite remote sensing technology to realize accurate fertilization, reduce agricultural input and reduce pollution. On the other hand, satellite navigation technology can improve the standardized operation level of agricultural machinery in the field.
In the course of rice production this year, the farm expanded the operational area of satellite navigation unmanned seedling transplanting technology from 3,000 mu last year to 30,000 mu.
This technology makes the planting of seedlings more uniform, can maximize the utilization of sunlight and cultivated land resources, and can save 16 yuan per acre of labor cost.
Farms have tried new technologies such as informationization and intelligence in agricultural production, forming the largest group of agricultural machinery in China from the ground to the sky.
According to statistics, there are currently a total of 49,000 farm machinery units (pieces), and the comprehensive mechanization rate in the field has reached 99.8%.
The operation of agricultural machinery has achieved 100% GPS satellite navigation, 100% precision seeding in drylands and 100% high-power locomotive operation in drylands.
"Green agriculture, intelligent agriculture and digital agriculture are the direction of agricultural modernization."
Liu Hualien, director of Friendship Farm, said.
The key to agricultural modernization is scientific and technological progress.
Agricultural reclamation in Heilongjiang, represented by farms, has played a demonstration and leading role in the "aircraft carrier" of modern agriculture in recent years, and has initially established a modern agricultural industry system led by large-scale cultivation, standardized production and industrial management.
In the suburb of Friendship County, there is an agricultural machinery extensive reading garden with an area of 350,000 square meters.
There is a concentrated display of more than 140 (pieces) agricultural machinery tools introduced and used in Heilongjiang agricultural reclamation over the years.
These agricultural machinery and farm have witnessed the development of China's agricultural modernization.
Xie Xiao Family for Everyone --Anhui Hefei Jiang Kou River Union Direct Attack on Mass Transfer - Xinhua Net
Xinhua News Agency, Hefei, July 26, Telegram Question: Xie Xiao Family for Everyone - Anhui Hefei Jiang Kou River Union Direct Attack on Mass Transfer
Xinhua News Agency reporters Chen Shangying, Wang Liwu, Liu Xia Village
At more than 4 p.m. on July 25, Fu Kunbao, wearing mud-covered rubber shoes, went from the front room to the back room, and his wife Zhou Yan was busy packing things back and forth.
"I received a phone call from village cadres to allow the transfer, and I was still mowing grass in the field."
Fu Kunbao said that he moved more than 60 acres of land and planted rice, which is now growing well. "I also took medicine yesterday, and the tools and everything have not been packed up yet."
Fu Kunbao pointed to the pesticide sprayer placed in the corner. "No one wants their home to be flooded, give up a small home for everyone."
In order to cope with the continued high water level pressure of Chaohu Lake and possible heavy rainfall, Hefei City, Anhui Province, is ready to use the Jiangkou River Union, where Fu Kunbao's family is located, to divert flood water on the 26th.
Jiang Kou Lianhe is located in Feixi County, next to Chaohu Causeway.
There are thousands of villagers involved in Yandian Township and Sanhe Town that need to be relocated.
As of 16: 00 on May 25, the water level of Chaohu, the fifth largest freshwater lake in China, remained at a high of 13.2 meters, exceeding the guaranteed water level by 0.7 meters.
Fu Kun Bao's kitchen was clean and tidy, with a pot of pumpkin head dishes on the table, eggs and some brine in the fridge.
"I didn't expect to move, the water of Jiangkou River looks good at present."
Zhou Yan said that the home is a bungalow, and some large items have not thought about where to put for the time being.
"Pack up the expensive items first. Large items such as refrigerators and TV sets can be temporarily placed in the homes of high-lying neighbors or relatives."
Village cadre Wang Lijing gave Fu Kun Bao advice.
Wang Lijing was responsible for the transfer and resettlement of 13 villagers, notifying each household and confirming each person's resettlement plan.
The nearest settlement to Fu Kun Bao's home is Su Xiaoxue, Yan Dian Township, about 2 kilometers away.
In addition to large pieces, Fu Kunbao and his family have a headache of more than 1000 jin of grain and some newly bought furniture.
"The grain is ready to be dragged to relatives' homes, the furniture can not be moved."
After a discussion, the couple put a stool under the newly bought bed and raised the bed by about half a meter.
At 6 p.m., Fu Kunbao began to use a tricycle to transport things to relatives' homes, and Zhou Yan continued to clean up at home.
At more than 11: 00 p.m., the couple looked in front of and behind the home, pulled on the electric switch, ready to go to the placement site.
"I hope the water will recede early."
Fu Kunbao said.
At 9: 30 a.m. on July 26, the reporter saw that the local area had made all preparations before the flood diversion.
