Xinhua News Agency, Guangzhou, July 26 (reporter Mao Xin) learned from the Guangdong Maritime Police Bureau that recently, the Bureau, in conjunction with the customs and public security departments of Guangzhou, broke down a large smuggling gang of refined oil products, and preliminarily verified that the gang had smuggled about 120,000 tons of refined oil products since 2019, with a case value of about 800 million yuan and tax evasion of about 240 million yuan.
The Guangdong Maritime Police Bureau and the anti-smuggling department of the Customs have gradually mapped out the division of personnel and organizational structure of the group.
On July 8, the maritime police, customs and public security departments carried out unified net collection operations in Guangzhou, Foshan and other places, as well as in the sea area of the Pearl River Estuary, respectively, seizing four suspected smuggling vessels on the spot, seizing a total of 4,700 tons of refined oil products from the vessels involved and the oil depots, and freezing a number of fund accounts.
It is understood that a total of eight ships and two helicopters were deployed in the joint operation, which was divided into multiple operational groups to work together to carry out a full-chain crackdown on links such as maritime smuggling and illegal operations on land, and all 35 major criminal suspects arrived at the case.
The case is currently under further investigation.
The relevant person in charge of the Guangdong Maritime Police Bureau said that it would continue to maintain a high-pressure situation in the future, crack down on all kinds of illegal and criminal smuggling activities at sea and maintain good order in the maritime areas under its jurisdiction.
Hurricane Hanna makes landfall in Texas or causes river surges and flash floods
At 5: 00 p.m. local time on July 25, Hurricane "Hanna" made landfall in the U.S. state of Texas, which will bring strong winds, torrential rain, swollen rivers and possibly life-threatening flash floods, according to a comprehensive foreign media report.
The National Hurricane Center says Hurricane Hanna is expected to bring heavy rainfall across parts of southern and northeastern Texas, causing swollen streams and life-threatening flash flooding.
It was reported that the area most affected by Hurricane Hanna was south of the city of Corpus Christi to the mouth of the Rio Grande, while widespread flash flooding could occur in the Rio Grande Valley.
Texas Governor Abbott said on the 25th: "Any hurricane is a huge challenge."
Thirty-two counties in the state declared a disaster emergency due to the hurricane.
The city of Corpus Christi, with a population of more than 320,000, has closed its libraries and museums and residents are waiting.
Abbott also said the hurricane cannot be allowed to bring more casualties to Texas at a time when the state is being hit hard by the new outbreak.
It is reported that precipitation in southern Texas is expected to reach 6 to 12 inches on the night of the 26th, and 3 to 5 inches of rain will also occur in northern Texas and coastal Louisiana.
Due to global warming and other factors, Hanna formed earlier than previous Atlantic hurricane seasons.
Typically, the first hurricane in the Atlantic does not form until mid-August.
Poland to withdraw from European treaty to prevent violence against women
Poland's Justice Ministry said Saturday that Poland will take steps next week to withdraw from the European treaty on the prevention of violence against women.
Poland's right-wing government cabinet said the treaty violated the rights of students' parents by requiring schools to teach students about gender issues.
Speaking at a press conference, Polish Justice Minister Joblo said his ministry will submit a request to the Ministry of Labor and Family Monday to start withdrawing from the treaty.
That treaty is also known as the Istanbul Convention.
"The treaty contains elements of a meaning-form nature that we consider harmful," Gioblo said.
Poland's ruling Law and Justice Party and its ruling coalition partners have a close alliance with the Roman Catholic Church and advocate a conservative social agenda.
Polish President Andrzej Duda made hostility to gay rights one of his main issues during his successful re-election campaign this month.
On Friday, thousands of Poles (mostly women) protested in Warsaw and other cities against the withdrawal.
"The purpose of withdrawing from the treaty is to legitimize domestic violence," Lempat, one of the protest organizers, said at a protest march in Warsaw.
Some protesters held banners reading "Law and Justice is a hell for women."
PiS has long complained about the Istanbul Convention.
Poland's previous centrist government ratified the Convention in 2015.
The PiS government said the treaty did not respect religion and called for liberal social policies to be taught in schools.
To date, however, the party has not decided to withdraw from the Convention.
(According to Reuters)
