The FAA ordered an urgent inspection of 2,000 Boeing airliners.
The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) issued an emergency airworthiness directive on the 24th, requiring an emergency inspection of about 2,000 Boeing 737NG and 737 Classic aircraft registered in the United States, because the corrosion of the air check valves of the above-mentioned aircraft could cause the engines to stop in the air.
The FAA said that so far, it has received four reports of 737NG and 737Classic engines stopping in the air, so it has made a request for an urgent inspection of airliners that have been parked for more than seven consecutive days and those that have flown less than 11 times since re-entering flight.
The Federal Aviation Administration warned that if the stage 5 check valves of all two engines were corroded, they could jam in the open position, causing the aircraft to lose power and be unable to restart the engines.
The aviation regulator ordered that once the check valve was found to be corroded, air operators must replace this key component before the aircraft could be put into service again.
Boeing responded later in the day that the outbreak of the new epidemic had reduced travel demand, resulting in many airliners being sealed or less used, and "check valves are more vulnerable to corrosion."
At the same time, Boeing said it had advised air carriers to inspect the airliners covered by the directive and that if problems were found, Boeing would provide assistance in repairing and replacing check valves.
Major US airline operators' airliners usually fly several times a day, but a large number of airliners have been grounded after the outbreak of the new epidemic, and some have returned to operation as passenger travel demand has recently grown slowly, AP reported.
The FAA did not release details of the four air parking reports.
Alaska Airlines revealed one of the incidents late on the 24th.
The airline operator said in a statement that one of its aircraft was flying from Seattle, Washington, to Austin, Texas on July 15 when one of its engines suddenly failed, and the aircraft finally made a successful emergency landing at Austin Airport.
Alaska Airlines said it had replaced the aircraft's engines and had inspected the engines of six aircraft in accordance with FAA directives.
American Airlines, United Airlines and Southwest Airlines said on the 24th that their airliners had no engine failure related to the air check valve.
Four American Airlines aircraft will be inspected and 28 United Airlines aircraft will be inspected.
Delta Air Lines said it would inspect its 20 aircraft, but did not say whether there had been any engine failures.
Several media reported that the FAA emergency airworthiness directive is another blow to Boeing.
A Boeing 737 MAX from Lion Air Indonesia and Ethiopian Airlines crashed in October 2018 and March 2019, respectively, killing 346 people.
This series of airliners was subsequently grounded worldwide, stopped production in January this year, and resumed production in May.
FAA Director Steve Dickson admitted in June that the FAA had "made a mistake" in regulating Boeing with regard to the 737MAX.
