Kochai Xili Tibetan antelope enters migration season
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, July 25, by wire (reporter Wang Jinjin) The reporter learned from the Wudaoliang Protection Station of the Kokoxili Management Office of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, Changjiang Yuan Park, that monitoring showed that the Tibetan antelope that had previously migrated to the Zhonai Lake area in the hinterland of Kokoxili to give birth to their offspring were gradually ending their calves and began to return to their original habitat with their young.
Surveillance footage near the Wudaoliang Protection Station shows that on July 25, about 40 female Tibetan antelope led three Tibetan antelope cubs through 3002 km of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway and the Wudaoliang North Bridge of the Qinghai-Tibet Railway. The Tibetan antelope has begun to move back.
According to expert analysis, in recent years, the number of Tibetan antelope young in returning sheep accounts for a quarter to a fifth of the total number of Tibetan antelope herds.
"In the early stage of remigration, the Tibetan antelope faces a higher risk of being preyed upon, so the number of young in the sheep will be relatively small, and there may even be no young," said Lien Xinming, an associate researcher at the Northwest Plateau Institute of Biology of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
According to the statistics of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration, the number of Tibetan antelope relocating is generally increasing year by year. In 2019, the number of Tibetan antelope relocating was 4,860, 338 more than in 2018.
"The return migration of Tibetan antelope this year is expected to end in early September, and the number of returning Tibetan antelope is still expected to continue to increase," Lien said.
The Tibetan antelope is a nationally protected animal.
At the end of May every year, Tibetan antelopes from Sanjiangyuan in Qinghai, Qiangtang in Tibet and Aljinshan in Xinjiang go to Zhonai Lake, located in the hinterland of Kokoxili, to give birth.
Wu Xiaomin, a Chinese expert on Tibetan antelope protection and researcher at the Shaanxi Provincial Institute of Zoology (Northwest Institute of Endangered Animals), said: "The return migration of Tibetan antelope is a process in which female Tibetan antelope return to their habitat with their young after giving birth. At first, the return group leaving the breeding site is relatively large, but then the Tibetan antelope will return to their respective habitat along different paths according to different geographical populations."
In order to ensure the safe return of Tibetan antelope groups, the reporter learned that the management office of the Changjiang Source Park of the Sanjiangyuan National Park Administration has arranged for staff to continuously carry out video monitoring and district patrols in the main return areas.
If a herd of Tibetan antelope is found trying to cross the road, the mountain patrol team will carry out temporary traffic control at the first time to allow the sheep to pass safely through the wildlife passage and ensure that they are subject to as little human interference as possible during their return migration.
