France Increases Military Investment in Space - Xinhua
French Defense Minister Florence Parly said on the 24th that France will add hundreds of millions of euros to its space defense budget to develop its space military forces in order to guard against possible "unfriendly actions" by other countries in outer space.
On the same day, Parly told Le Provence that between 2019 and 2025, the expenditure budget for French military space projects will increase from the previously proposed 3.6 billion euros (about US $4.2 billion) to 4.3 billion euros (US $5 billion).
In accordance with the Act on French Military Planning 2019-2025, approved by the French Parliament in 2018, France is expected to upgrade its existing observation and communications satellites, launch three electromagnetic interception satellites and modernize its space surveillance radar.
French President Emmanuel Macron announced last July that a military space command and an "aviation and space force" would be established within the French Air Force.
Parley said she will officially announce the creation of the space force when she visits a military school in Salon, Provence, later this month.
Parley said the space force is part of the Air Force and will have a strength of 500 by 2025.
"The idea that space serves the common interests of science is gone forever. Today, space is a place where countries compete for global hegemony," she said.
Parly reiterated Macron's previous statement that France has no intention of provoking an arms race.
"We are by no means engaged in an arms race. But it is my responsibility to be fully aware of the threats we may face."
Palley recalled the surveillance of a military satellite shared by France and Italy in 2017.
She said the "sneak peek" was a Russian satellite.
The Russian side denied this claim.
Parly said France would "soon" have small patrol satellites capable of detecting and targeting "those behind unfriendly actions."
The French media believe that the reason why France seeks to establish a space force is due to the fact that US President Donald Trump asked the US Department of Defense to draft a bill to establish a Pacific Air Force last February.
Trump signed the National Defense Authorization Act last December, approving the establishment of the Pacific Air Force, the sixth US military force.
Some experts worry that these US measures have accelerated the pace of US space militarization and could trigger a new arms race in space.
