Report says the shared accommodation market has picked up since March
According to the "China Shared Accommodation Development Report 2020" (hereinafter referred to as the "Report") recently released by the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center, the transaction volume of China's shared accommodation market decreased by 72.1% year-on-year in the first five months of 2020 due to the impact of the epidemic.
However, the shared accommodation market began to warm up since March, and the market turnover, order volume and reception number gradually recovered.
The Report shows that the volume of transactions in the shared accommodation market has declined significantly. On the one hand, due to the significant decline in the demand for travel and accommodation under the prevention and control of the epidemic, the number of orders decreased sharply, with the total number of orders falling by 65 per cent year-on-year and the number of receptions falling by 63 per cent year-on-year in the first five months. On the other hand, the weakness of demand also led to a more significant decrease in overnight prices, with the average overnight price falling by 16 per cent year-on-year in the first five months.
However, market turnover in March, April and May increased by 78%, 199% and 35% respectively; the number of orders increased by 141%, 152% and 50% respectively; and the number of receptions increased by 81%, 112% and 28% respectively.
The Report points out that the development of the shared accommodation industry has been promising for a long time, but there are still many uncertainties in the near future.
In this regard, Yu Fengxia, deputy director of the Sharing Economy Research Center of the National Information Center, told the Worker's Daily that the development of shared accommodation needs stronger policy support. On the one hand, it is necessary to do a good job in the implementation of the policies already issued in the previous period, further strengthen policy advocacy and coherence, and focus on creating a better business environment. On the other hand, it is also necessary to further strengthen policy guidance and support in terms of stimulating consumer demand, enriching the supply of tourism and accommodation services, innovating service methods and strengthening cooperation between the government and platform enterprises.
