In order to avoid the resulting risks, Xiao Wen, Mr. Wen and many other children and parents operate in the safe area designated by the softball team.
But then softball team member Chen Mou took off his hand while pitching, causing the softball to fly over the net to the above-mentioned safe area and hit Xiao Wen in the back of the head.
Mr. Wen immediately took Xiao Wen to the hospital for treatment and was diagnosed with head trauma.
Mr. Wen was of the view that the facilities of the school stadium did not comply with the relevant safety regulations and did not effectively manage the team and related facilities.
The school's negligence led to the above-mentioned events, which caused Xiao Wen to suffer great physical and mental suffering, as well as greater suffering to his family, for which the school should bear legal responsibility.
In response, the school argued that the school had set up a protective net in the playground and posted management regulations and training notices informing people to enter the playground at a safe distance from the training site and reminding them of their own safety. The plaintiff could not prove that the school had "failed to fulfil its safety and security obligations" and therefore did not agree to compensation.
After the hearing, the court held that the site of the incident was open to the public free of charge by the university involved. Although the school has a safety and security obligation to the management of the playground, this safety and security obligation only needs to meet the general duty of care.
At the time of the incident, the school set up a protective net in the playground, which had fulfilled its appropriate safety and security obligations, and Chen Mou also compensated Xiao Wen for more than 2,000 yuan in losses such as medical and transportation costs in accordance with the previous compensation agreement. The two sides agreed to settle the dispute at one time.
Later, Xiao Wen's parents again claimed compensation from the school, which was not based on the law, and the court ruled to reject all the plaintiffs' claims.
Neither party appealed the verdict, which is now in effect.
According to Article 37 of the Tort Liability Law of China, schools, as administrators of public places, have safety and security obligations; in cases where the actions of a third party cause damage to others, the third party bears the tort liability, while the administrators of public places who fail to fulfil their safety and security obligations shall bear the corresponding supplementary responsibilities.
The judge stated that since, as the manager of a public place, he is most likely to know the actual situation of the whole place, to anticipate the possible dangers and damage, and thus to take the necessary measures to prevent the loss or mitigate the extent of the damage, and the cost of avoiding and mitigating the damage is the lowest, the law stipulates that he shall bear the corresponding guarantee obligation to engage in social activities.
In this case, for the non-specific group of people who enter the playground open to the public free of charge, the safety and security obligations of the school should be commensurate with the social activities it engages in. In particular, it should mainly take basic safety measures and have the obligation to inform the hidden dangers.
In judicial practice, it is not appropriate to impose excessive safety and security obligations on the managers of public places.
If the school has taken measures to set up a protective net and fulfilled its obligation to inform, it can be concluded that the school is not at fault and should not bear legal liability.
In addition, with regard to the infringement of the third party, even if the administrators of schools and other public places fail to fulfil their safety and security obligations, their liability is also a supplement to damages. According to the newly promulgated Civil Code, after assuming the supplementary liability, the administrators can also recover compensation from the third party.
Therefore, in such accidents, after the victim has received compensation from the direct infringer, the scope of claim should not be expanded.
