Founder of Beijing Philharmonic Choir Yang Hongnian died at the age of 86.
Beijing News (reporter Liu Zhen) On July 26, the Beijing Philharmonic Choir published an obituary. Yang Hongnian, founder of the Beijing Philharmonic Choir, a famous Chinese conductor and music educator, a lifelong academic member of the Central Conservatory of Music and a professor of the Command Department, died in Beijing at 13: 55 on July 26, 2020, at the age of 86.
Photo from Beijing Philharmonic Choir official website.
Born in 1934, Yang Hongnian, a native of Nanjing, Jiangsu Province, has loved music since childhood.
He was the conductor of the choir of Nanjing People's Radio in 1951, and was admitted to the Music Department of East China Normal University in Shanghai in the autumn of 1951. He studied conducting under Professor Yang Jiaren and German conductor Hitzmann, and studied musical styles and polyphonic tunes by former Soviet expert Arzamanov.
In 1958, he taught in the Department of Music of the Beijing Art Normal College, and in 1973 he was transferred to the Department of Composition and Command of the Central Conservatory of Music.
Yang Hongnian founded the Beijing Philharmonic Choir in 1983.
Over the past 30 years, in keeping with the purpose of "love and dedication", he has led the choir to sing all over the world and won dozens of awards in important competitions at home and abroad.
He has conducted the performances of more than 30 groups, including the choir of the Central Orchestra, the Central Ethnic Song and Dance Ensemble, the Oriental Song and Dance Ensemble and the Shanghai Choir, and held a number of symphonic and choral concerts.
The works include "Band Training", "Choral Training", "Two Songs Writing", "Children's Songs" (the first and second volumes), "On the Problem of Choral Pronunciation", "On the Sound Level Layout of Orchestra Music", and translations of "Choral Instruments" and "Debussy's Harmonic Language".
Chongqing, July 26 (reporter Liu Xian) Chongqing Municipal Development and Reform Commission released news on July 26 that the city has so far returned 4,404 fishermen, accounting for 42.54% of all fishermen involved.
Li Daiguo, 53, said in an interview with CNN.com that his grandfather had been fishing in the Longxi River since he was 11 years old. He followed his father to fish, rocked his boat and walked along the Longxi River, up to Liangping in Chongqing and down to live a long life. Every time he left home, he lived for ten days and a half months, relying on fishing to support his family.
However, since 1997, with the gradual influx of the rural population into the town, there have been more and more residents in the town, causing more and more serious environmental pollution.
Paper mills, chemical plants and breeding farms have been built along the Longxi River, which also pollutes the river.
By 2007 and 2008, the Longxi River had become a smelly ditch.
"The scales of the fish caught are black, and when cut open, they are black inside."
Li Daiguo said fishing became more and more difficult after the river was polluted.
The local area began to make great efforts to control the pollution of the Longxi River, including cleaning and floating, river patrol, management and protection of aquatic resources, etc.
Li Daiguo also retired from fishing to production and became a member of the river patrol team to protect aquatic resources.
As of January 1, 2020, the Chongqing Aquatic Biological Reserve and the relevant waters of the main city have been completely banned from fishing.
According to the data of the Chongqing Municipal Development and Reform Commission, so far, Chongqing has accumulated 3,403 fishing vessels and 4,643 fishing vessels that have signed fishing agreements, accounting for 63.3 per cent and 86.3 per cent of the total three-year tasks, respectively.
There are 4,404 retired fishermen, accounting for 42.54% of all fishermen involved.
Of the 4,404 retired fishermen, 4,267 were employed, accounting for 96.89 per cent of the retired fishermen.
Old-age insurance covered 2,691 people, accounting for 61.10 per cent of the retired fishermen.
