Israel strengthens the prevention and control of repeated epidemics
2020-07-26 04: 56: 44 Source: Guangming Daily Author: Wang Sisuo Responsible Editor: Wang Sisuo
Israel strengthens prevention and control of repeated outbreaks
At the beginning of the outbreak of the new crown pneumonia, Israel's prevention and control measures were effective.
However, with the gradual lifting of the ban on prevention and control measures, the number of confirmed cases of new pneumonia in Israel has increased significantly recently, and the Israeli Government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On February 28, the first case of coronavirus pneumonia was confirmed in Israel itself. As a result, Israel quickly took measures to close all entry and exit points, suspend non-essential industries, switch schools to online classes, restrict public transport and non-essential social activities, block cities with serious outbreaks, and jointly maintain prevention and control measures.
This series of measures quickly achieved positive results, and by mid-May, the number of new confirmed cases of pneumonia in Israel in a single day had fallen to single digits.
With the epidemic under control and the complete lifting of all prevention and control measures in Israel, the number of new confirmed cases of crown pneumonia has gradually rebounded since June.
Especially since the beginning of July, the spread of the epidemic has been accelerating.
In recent days, the number of new daily cases in Israel has been more than 1,500 for eight days, and as of July 25, the number of new cases reached 916.
As of July 25, Israel had 59,745 confirmed cases and 448 deaths.
In the face of the rapid rebound of the epidemic, the Israeli Government has repeatedly taken urgent measures to strengthen the prevention and control of the epidemic.
On July 6, after the number of confirmed cases exceeded 30,000, the Israeli government closed gyms, swimming pools, bars, nightclubs and other places of public entertainment, and introduced a policy of restricting public transport, stipulating that the maximum number of passengers per bus should not exceed 20.
On the 17th, the Israeli government announced a series of new restrictions, including the implementation of "city closure" on weekends, stipulating that "city closure" should be implemented from 17: 00 every Friday to 5: 00 every Sunday.
During this period, people may go out, but places such as shops, shopping malls, hairdressers, beauty salons, libraries, zoos, museums, exhibition galleries, swimming pools and tourist attractions will be closed, while places of basic services such as supermarkets and pharmacies will remain open.
At the same time, gatherings of more than 10 people are prohibited on all days and hours, gyms, studios and other places will be closed, restaurants and cafes will be banned from eating, and only take-out services will be allowed.
At the same time, the Israeli people have not paid enough attention to the seriousness of the epidemic and have failed to form joint efforts with the government in combating the epidemic.
After repeated outbreaks in Israel, many people took to the streets to protest because the government's prevention and control measures affected their own economic interests.
On July 11, tens of thousands of people demonstrated in Tel Aviv, arguing that the anti-epidemic policy affected the economy.
On the evening of the 21st, thousands more protesters gathered in front of Prime Minister Netanyahu's official residence in Jerusalem to protest against Prime Minister Netanyahu's promulgation of preventive and control measures such as banning restaurants and coffee halls without providing corresponding compensation.
In addition, many people also failed to observe the rules of wearing masks and maintaining a safe social distance of two meters during outdoor activities. In order to avoid being fined by the police for not wearing a mask, many people only wore masks on their chin or hung them on their wrists.
During the repeated epidemics, the school was a major disaster area for the spread of the new crown virus, and according to a recent visit to the kindergarten by journalists, it was found that the teachers and students of the kindergarten did not wear masks as required by the government, nor did they maintain a safe social distance of two meters from each other, laying hidden dangers for a large number of teachers and students to be infected with the virus.
Professor Elie Waxman, a member of the Advisory Panel of Anti-epidemic Experts of the Israeli National Security Council, believed that Israel was moving towards a "dangerous situation", pointing out that the current measures taken by Israel to prevent and control the epidemic were not enough, and that all places of leisure and recreational activities and summer schools should be closed in order to control the further spread of the epidemic.
Waxman said that Israel lacks an overall plan to combat the epidemic, and that all departments of the parliament and government should abandon their respective interests as soon as possible, reach agreement on combating the epidemic and formulate clear steps that include relevant restrictions in different sectors.
