Lancet article praises China's anti-epidemic efforts and encourages countries to learn from experience
As a country with a population of 1.4 billion and a scale similar to that of Europe or the United States, China has effectively controlled the new epidemic at this stage, without further widespread transmission, and has largely controlled the epidemic in the country, The Lancet said in its 25th issue.
The article said that in the past decade or so, China has invested heavily in domestic research and public health construction, which has made China much more prepared for the new crown than it was for the severe acute respiratory syndrome (SARS).
The authors say that at the time of the SARS outbreak in 2002, China was initially ill-prepared, especially as the pathogen could not be identified.
When the new crown virus was discovered in December 2019, Chinese scientists were soon able to identify the type of virus and shared the genome sequencing data with the international community on January 11, 2020.
By the end of January, doctors from mainland China and Hong Kong had clarified the clinical characteristics of the virus and warned the world of the threat of the new crown virus through research papers published in The Lancet.
China has also always been at the forefront of vaccine research. Under the declaration of a national emergency and through close domestic cooperation, such research has been carried out very quickly and rigorously. In May and July, respectively, the results of the progress made in the early trials of the new crown vaccine developed by China were published in The Lancet.
China's experience has shown that it is very important to invest in the national health and research system and effectively improve laboratory capacity.
This is the basis for a rapid and effective national response to health emergencies and global health security.
Other countries, especially low- and middle-income countries, are well worth learning from.
In addition, China's experience has proved that, on the basis of strong research, strong high-level officials must make correct decisions decisively on the basis of scientific evidence in order for the new epidemic to be effectively controlled.
The article stressed that the government and its leaders must respect science, understand its value and act on it in the best way for society.
At the beginning of the outbreak, China's National Health and Construction Commission sent three groups of infectious disease experts to Wuhan to investigate the risk and spread of the new crown virus, and their suggestions provided the basis for the decision to "seal off" Wuhan on January 23. When the experts put forward the necessity and urgency of building a square cabin hospital, the government quickly made a decision and implemented it quickly. At the same time, the extensive participation of the community and the masses also enabled the epidemic to be controlled quickly and effectively.
Finally, the article emphasizes that in response to the global health emergency, countries need to strengthen global cooperation and joint response.
